Hello, Yeah I was sleeping, then back to the code I found that : 

The TextureLoader contains a load methode, the load methode needs the onProgress from the TextureLoader parameter because the TextureLoader.load() contains an ImageLoader that is supposed to launch it back when the Image is loading. Buuuuut, the ImageLoader is restricted : 
//commented in the source
/*
		image.addEventListener( 'progress', function ( event ) {
			if ( onProgress ) onProgress( event );
		}, false );
		*/

That's because an image is not able to onProgress(event);

I misunderstood the whole thing, now I get it.

Then I need to override the Textureloader's ImageLoader() to load my image as file (using a FileLoader onProgress-able). Then I'll use the default ImageLoader to load the file previously loaded with the FileLoader as normal.

And after my brain is back to work I saw your answer :), now I have a base code, really good timing  thanks a lot.


EDIT : 

Sorry again, that's not really working...
I got some change, I can see the onProgress is "working" but my xhr.loaded/xhr.total update only twice : 

values : 
first value : 0.002165356541209468
second value jump to : 1


On the top of my code I override the  ImageLoader  prototype this way : 

THREE.ImageLoader.prototype = {

    load: function ( url, onLoad, onProgress, onError ) {

        var scope = this;

        var image = document.createElementNS( 'http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml', 'img' );
        image.onload = function () {

            image.onload = null;

            URL.revokeObjectURL( image.src );

            if ( onLoad ) onLoad( image );

            scope.manager.itemEnd( url );

        };
        image.onerror = onError;

        var loader = new THREE.FileLoader();
        loader.setPath( this.path );
        loader.setResponseType( 'blob' );
        loader.setWithCredentials( this.withCredentials );
        loader.load( url, function ( blob ) {

            image.src = URL.createObjectURL( blob );

        }, onProgress, onError );

        scope.manager.itemStart( url );

        return image;

    },

    setCrossOrigin: function ( value ) {

        this.crossOrigin = value;
        return this;

    },

    setWithCredentials: function ( value ) {

        this.withCredentials = value;
        return this;

    },

    setPath: function ( value ) {

        this.path = value;
        return this;

    }

}

And in my code : 

material.map = new THREE.TextureLoader(manager).load(jsonArrayMaterialsOptions[index].texture,undefined, function(xhr) {console.log(xhr.loaded/xhr.total);});

I'm going crazy, I don't understand why a large image can't update its percent more than 2 times.
